@nalyat In case you still care, I had the same problem and was able to get it to work using lambdas:

Function accepting a PyObject*
```
   c.def_static( "fromArray", []( py::handle obj ) {
         PyObject* a = obj.ptr();
         return Dbl3Vec::fromArray( a );
      } );
```

Function returning a PyObject*
```
   c.def( "toArray", []( const Dbl3Vec& self ) {
         PyObject* r = self.toArray();
         return py::handle( r );
      } );
```

This should do the trick:
```c++
class A {
public:
    virtual ~A() = default;

protected:
    virtual int foo() { return 42; }
};

class PublicA : public A {
public:
    using A::foo;
};

class Trampoline : public A {
public:
    int foo() override { PYBIND11_OVERLOAD(int, A, foo, ); }
};

PYBIND11_MODULE(cmake_example, m) {
    py::class_<A, Trampoline>(m, "A")
        .def(py::init<>())
        .def("foo", &PublicA::foo);
}
```

Again, `PublicA` is used only to bypass the `protected` access modifier. Apart from that, everything is the same as described in the docs for `public` virtual functions.

